AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.the large white Ford pickup truck: Vehicle in which Michael Brett Jacquinot was a passenger during the United States/Mexican Border Patrol stop, bearing a Kansas license plate and appearing suspicious due to its presence in Big Bend National Park on a Sunday morning
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.United States/Mexican Border Patrol: Law enforcement agency responsible for border control and patrol
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.Big Bend National Park: Location along the United States/Mexican Border where vehicle sensors are located and where a recent narcotics smuggling operation originated
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.Alpine, Texas: Location where United States/Mexican Border Patrol Agents Andrew P. Graham and Jay Snodgrass were stationed, and area from which Big Bend National Park typically hires contractors
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.Marfa Sector Area Operations Center: Previous work location of United States/Mexican Border Patrol Agent Jay Snodgrass
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.Laredo, Texas, border area: Previous work location of United States/Mexican Border Patrol Agent Jay Snodgrass
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.marked United States/Mexican Border Patr: Vehicles used by United States/Mexican Border Patrol agents for patrol and surveillance
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.a late model four-door sedan: Vehicle observed by United States/Mexican Border Patrol, carrying an older Anglo couple
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.the computer-system: System used by the United States/Mexican Border Patrol for registration information, which experienced problems during the pursuit of the large white Ford pickup truck
